																				<div class="sg-editor">
						
<p>Since 1965, the Mr. Olympia light has shined brightly on the Men’s open category. In this, the biggest and best bodybuilders in the world compete for the elusive Sandow trophy. However times change, and so do tastes.</p>



<p>Since its introduction in 2016, the Classic Olympia division has continued to rise in popularity and competitors. Just this year, 64 classic athletes qualified for the Mr. Olympia. While this may be too many, it&#8217;s certainly a sign of its aesthetic appeal.&nbsp;</p>



<p>With a small waist and large V-Taper, the classic physique bodybuilders of today are bringing back the iconic golden era. Nearly 50 years after he retired, the classical Arnold Schwarzenegger look continues to shine. In the present day, the light shines brightest on none other than the classic physique icon, Chris Bumstead.</p>



<p>By becoming the Men’s Classic Physique Olympia 2024 winner, he won his sixth and possibly last title. So, who exactly is Chris Bumstead, and what makes him so popular? We take a detailed look at his career and lifestyle below!</p>



<figure class="wp-block-table"><table><thead><tr><th>Chris Bumstead’s Profile</th><th></th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Nickname</td><td>CBum</td></tr><tr><td>Weight</td><td>215–225 pounds</td></tr><tr><td>Height</td><td>6 feet 1 inch</td></tr><tr><td>Age</td><td>29-years-old</td></tr><tr><td>Date of Birth</td><td>February 2nd, 1995</td></tr><tr><td>Nationality</td><td>Canadian</td></tr><tr><td>Highlights</td><td>Mr. Olympia Men’s Classic Physique 2024 Champion</td></tr></tbody></table><figcaption class="wp-element-caption">Chris Bumstead’s Profile</figcaption></figure>



<div class="wp-block-group ft-snippet is-layout-constrained wp-block-group-is-layout-constrained"><div class="wp-block-group__inner-container">
<p class="has-medium-font-size">Chris Bumstead — A Bodybuilding Icon</p>



<p>Chris Bumstead is a 30-year-old six-time Classic Physique Champion whose legacy will last for generations.</p>



<ul>
<li>Chris was born and raised in Ottawa, Canada. As a kid, he was extremely active in high school playing football, basketball, and track and field.</li>



<li>He was introduced to bodybuilding by his brother-in-law and ex-IFBB pro, Ian Valliere. At 19 years old, Ian saw potential and helped Chris prepare for his first competition.</li>



<li>He began competing in 2015 and shortly after won his pro card. He entered the Olympia in 2017, twice coming second before winning six titles.</li>



<li>He retired recently following his Mr. Olympia Classic Physique Division 2024 win, leaving a lasting legacy.</li>
</ul>
</div></div>



<h2 class="wp-block-heading">Chris’ Early Stages</h2>



<p>Christopher Adam Bumstead, popularly known as <em>CBum, </em>grew up in Ottawa, Canada. He was extremely active in high school, playing football, basketball, and competing in track and field.&nbsp;</p>



<p>During his youth, he idolized the legendary Tom Platz because of his amazing leg development. He also watched Arnold Schwarzenegger in his multiple acting roles after his iconic bodybuilding career.&nbsp;</p>



<p>He was first introduced to bodybuilding by his brother-in-law Ian Valiere, an International Fitness and Bodybuilding (IFBB) pro with a successful open career. Ian saw potential in Chris and helped him prepare for his first competition in 2014 at the age of just 19 years old</p>



<p>Chris saw Ian as his brother-in-law, coach, friend, and protector who helped him navigate the dangers of the bodybuilding world. Ian was the constant support figure during Chris’s early rise, something which he always credits and thanks him for.&nbsp;</p>



<h2 class="wp-block-heading">Chris Bumstead&#8217;s Achievements</h2>



<p>Chris began competing in 2014 at 19 years old while being prepped and coached by Ian. In the following year, he competed at the 2015 CBBF Canadian National Bodybuilding Championship. During this, he took first place in the Men’s Junior Division.&nbsp;</p>



<p>After only two more competitions he won his pro card at just 21 years old. This was in the 2016 IFBB North American Championships as a heavyweight before the Classic division existed.&nbsp;</p>



<p>In the same year, the Classic division was introduced to the sport of bodybuilding. Chris switched to this and quickly found his calling, competing three times and winning two of them.&nbsp;</p>



<p>In 2017, he made his classic debut at the 2017 Mr. Olympia. During this year and the next, he came second behind two-time champion and now friend, Breon Ansley. This was a hotly contested rivalry, often leading to disagreements and arguments at the press conferences.&nbsp;</p>



<p>During this, Chris’s potential to win the title was obvious. His shape and muscle symmetry gave him a classic look that Breon found hard to match. However, at that time the judges preferred a classic look with more muscle.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>



<p>In 2019, he won his first Classic Olympia title, dethroning Breon even though he had hernia surgery months out from the show. His victory caused controversy with Breon’s coach and former IFBB pro, Chris Cormier who thought the results were unfair.&nbsp;</p>



<p>This rivalry continued over the next two years with similar arguments and shots at the 2022 Olympia press conference. However, Breon dropped down to third while Chris pulled away from the other athletes, winning two more titles. Chris and Breon put aside their rivalry and became friends while continuing to battle each other.</p>



<p>Midway through his prep in 2022, he announced that he would be coached by Hany Rambod. Hany is a well-known trainer of many elite bodybuilders including the open champion Hadi Choopan and 212 and open champion Derek Lunsford.</p>



<p>Throughout the next three years, he cemented his place as a classical icon by dominating the Olympia competition. He defeated well-known competitors such as Urs Kalecinski and Romon Rocha Queiroz, with each judge giving him first with no hesitation.&nbsp;</p>



<p>With this, he set the standard before sensationally retiring in the recent Mr. Olympia 2024 event.</p>



<h3 class="wp-block-heading">Key Career Milestones</h3>



<ul>
<li><strong>2015 CBBF Canadian National Bodybuilding Championship Men’s Junior Division — </strong>1st.</li>



<li><strong>2016 CBBF Bodybuilding Championships Open Heavyweight Division — </strong>2nd.</li>



<li><strong>2016 IFBB North American Championships, Heavyweight — 1st</strong> (Earned IFBB Pro Card).</li>



<li><strong>2016 IFBB Dayana Cadeau Classic, Classic Physique —</strong> 3rd.</li>



<li><strong>2017 IFBB Pittsburgh Pro, Classic Physique —</strong> 1st.</li>



<li><strong>2017 IFBB Toronto Pro, Classic Physique —</strong> 1st.</li>



<li><strong>2017 Mr. Olympia, Classic Physique — </strong>2nd.</li>



<li><strong>2018 Mr. Olympia, Classic Physique —</strong> 2nd.</li>



<li><strong>2019 Mr. Olympia, Classic Physique — </strong>1st.</li>



<li><strong>2020 Mr. Olympia, Classic Physique — </strong>1st.</li>



<li><strong>2021 Mr. Olympia, Classic Physique —</strong> 1st.</li>



<li><strong>2022 Mr. Olympia, Classic Physique —</strong> 1st.</li>



<li><strong>2023 Mr. Olympia, Classic Physique —</strong> 1st.</li>



<li><strong>2024 Mr. Olympia, Classic Physique —</strong> 1st (Retired).</li>
</ul>



<h2 class="wp-block-heading">His Departure From Bodybuilding</h2>



<p>Over the last few years, rumors circulated regarding Chris’s retirement but nothing really came of it. His struggles with IgA Nephropathy, an autoimmune disease, and multiple injuries are well-documented. He’s torn his bicep, lat, and quad muscles, leading people to wonder how long he’ll continue.&nbsp;</p>



<p>Throughout this, Chris persevered and came out on top, winning five titles despite the injuries and struggles.&nbsp;</p>



<p>This year, rumors gained more traction after his recent marriage to Ms. Bikini Olympia champion Courtney King now Courtney Bumstead. The arrival of their baby girl, Bradley Shay Bumstead, future added to this, with people wondering what’s next.</p>



<p>Before this all happened, Chris had long stated that he would pull back from bodybuilding at the age of 30. With next year marking his 30th birthday, the combination of injury, family, and age made retirement even more possible.</p>



<p>When accepting this year&#8217;s award, Chris started by saying <strong>“I think a lot of people know what&#8217;s coming today”</strong>. Following this, he shocked the audience by saying the words no one wanted to hear.</p>



