<p>His departure leaves a huge hole in the classic physique community. However, it also paves the way for a new, exciting group of classic athletes to take the spotlight. Especially after Mike Sommerfeld jumped from eighth place to second within just a year.</p>



<p>In the post-Olympia press conference, Chris stated that he’ll be taking lots of time off with his family. He reminded everyone of his love for the Classic division by saying that he wants to work with the Olympia. He thanked the owners again and even stated that he’ll be putting up some extra prize money next year!</p>



<p>Despite his retirement, we don’t think this is the last we’ve seen of Chris Bumstead. While it may not be on stage, we think he’ll continue inspiring generations in different ways for years to come.</p>



<h2 class="wp-block-heading list-start">Inside Chris Bumstead’s Workout Routine</h2>



<p>Chris uses a diverse mix of compound free-weight movements to form the backbone of his training. He likes to develop strength in the foundational movements while mixing in some variety.</p>



<p>He tends to use a high-volume approach before going to failure on his final set. With this, he mixes strength-type training with bodybuilding volume work. However, he never tends to go for one rep maximum attempts or true low-volume training.&nbsp;</p>



<p>His cardio is performed as needed based on his progress during the offseason and his prep. He regularly practices posing most days, including his trademark vacuum pose.&nbsp;</p>



<p>Chris’s training approaches have changed massively since his introduction to the sport. His recent trainer, Hany Rambod, focuses on using Fascia Stretch Training or FST-7.&nbsp;</p>



<p>This involves performing seven high-repetition, high-intensity sets of an exercise with minimal rest at the end of a workout. Hany believes this will stretch the muscle tissue fascia, allowing for more muscle growth. Alongside this, he implements static holds, partial reps, and forced reps.&nbsp;</p>



<p>Let’s take a look at some examples of Chris’s workouts. These change regularly meaning these give you a small snippet of what his training looks like.&nbsp;</p>



<p>He tends to split his training up into six sessions with two rest days. This rotates through an eight-day period.</p>



<p>He trains his chest twice as this is his favorite body part. He does two back sessions as this is something he’s been told to bring up by the judges.&nbsp;</p>



